Giving some feedback again.

>Wolfox
Sadly I don't know much about World of Warcraft beyond what I experience in Warcraft 3: Reign of Chaos.
That said, in my opinion you've got a good balance of origin story and background lore. The Worgan/Human couple feel great as characters, and I'm curious to see how the introduction of the Vulpera will affect them. I personally have a particular outcome I'd prefer, but I still look forward to how the story progresses.

>First Contact Procedures
This feels like Mass Effect in all the best ways. It does feel that there is a whole story that deserves exploring that occurs before this one.
The title is first contact, but there is a lot of indication that these aliens are not the first the humans have contacted. I could understand better if the story was writen more from the Alie POV, especially considering the First Contact focal point of the story.
Also, unless I missed a portion that did so, please give us a more in-detail description of these aliens? The six-eyes element of the Vishan is clear, but what about the rest of their physique beyond being smaller than humans? Also, how do the Sentre differ?

>Electrolocation
Great cute story with an adorable moment between these two. The focus of explaining a unique sense is handled very well, with the comparison to blindness feeling appropriate.

>Coiled with Torque
This and OTF Both do great to utilise the lore of the franchise they're based on, as I personally have little experience with it, but understand enough of the lore for them.
I do like Coiled, but I do feel that despite the small time skip that Torque goes from mocking the monkey to wanting to fuck him a little too quick.
I want to suggest at least one or more instances where Safeguard saves Torque, but that may just be the male power fantasy slipping through.
Great written lewd by the way. God damn I wish I was Safeguard.

Mirror Spider

>On the Fringes
Great story so far, especially with how the relationship was progressing. Vee's intelligence is very well presented.
The lose the Protag feels at the end is damn devastating. Well written gut punch to the reader in a story that in hindsight was definitely going too smoothly. The sudden spike of action was timed well in my opinion.

>Slime and Steel
Good short story.
I do have one gripe, which is calling her a snail. It feels more like a throwaway detail than something pivotal for the plot. This somewhat manifests as an iritation to me when she undresses, and unless I missed it, there is no mention of a shell or shell-like structure that a snail character would have. Without that, you might as well call her a slug, which feels like it would provide better hooks for insuts, but that is just my feeling.
I am curious if this one will be progressed. How does the Knights' family react to his choice of maiden, let alone that she is not human? It feels implied that cross-species pregnancy is a thing, but how would the result of that affect a noble family? Blood Purists may consider the half-caste child as grounds for the knights to be expelled from the family, so how would the knight react?

>I-77
I'm enjoying the world building and characters. The fact Francis isn't abusive (without reason) to his hostages is pleasent to see given how some Other anons would likely have acted in the situation.

>Acid Rain: Just a Drop
I damn near thought you were rebooting the story from scratch. Never done any hallucinogens, but from what I've heard from others you've written the experience very well, and the alternate POV of events caused by it.

To all the writers, keep up the great work.
If I didn't leave feedback to your story, I can only say that sometimes a story just doesn't hook me the right way.

Well there's varying degrees of fiction, especially when talking about science fiction. Trying to keep the fiction to the realm of possibility is what most prefer from their science fiction (that generally being having a certain scientific breakthrough happen in your story). If you created a universe where humanity had found a way to produce exotic matter then you could have people traveling between planets, solar systems, and galaxies via wormholes and that would be entirely realistic since, as far as we know, the current absence of exotic matter is what's stopping us from doing such a thing. You could also very well have a story that doesn't break from any science and still have human colonies on and around several objects within the solar system with Earth having over a trillion people living in giant city towers while also having thousands of habitats in orbit with artificial gravity from spinning with a hundred billion more living there and have everyone living like the one percent of the one percent live nowadays. You could also have a story where a single man flies around the galaxy collapsing stars into black holes for the sake of resetting the universe because he can bend gravity to his will and just hand wave it away with some sort of quantum bullshit.

Anonymous Sat 20 Jun 2020 22:45:54 No.31033925 Report

>>31033731
I don't recommend Hemingway. It's useful for highlighting adverbs, but honestly the search function is more useful if you think you are using "just" too much or some other frequent word. But Hemingway is really aggressive on how low that number should be for adverbs.

It can also be misleading because of dialogue. People don't speak like good prose and you will often find Hemingway's advice being devastating to how you want a character to talk.

If you want to have fun find some sample chapters of books you like and see what Hemingway does to them. I stopped giving it much weight after I did that a few times and almost always sided with the author's choice over Hemingway.
